{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hooloovoo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656859/1920121001/0476.xml":{"full_text":"OHHEBH\nt IN AIDBFEXPITS\nbtl/L ruannc.\nThe much-talked-of and vary ltn(portant\nAmerican bankers' conference\non foreign trade financing open,\ned this morning in Chicago, with\nJohn McHugh, chairman of the A. B.\nA. committee on aiding foreign buaiaess,\npresiding.\nIn his opening address Mr. McHugh\nrailed attention to conditions existing\n?efore the war; to the fact that the\nUnited States was a debtor nation,\nthat out of onr earnings from raili\nroads, mills and factories we sent\nabroad each year t200.Me.000 in settlpmpnt\nnf 1nt?rpitt ktiH navmf?nt nt\ndividends.\nEurope had loaned to us and invested\nin a large degree in oar railroads\nand as a result our exports exceeded\nour imports. \"We depended on London\nto finance such foreign trade as\nwe had.\n\"The pound sterling was the currency\nof international commerce. We\nhad no co-ordained banking system,\nno discount market and no machinery\nfor developing one. We organised no\nmachinery finance export sales on a\nfround, orderly, systematic way.\"\nComparison was made with the\nmethods of Great Britain, with foreign\ntrade Its life blood.\nThen came the dramatic change\nvwin ine war, wnen me antes lurneu j\nto the United States with the enor-;\nmous trade from this side, financed j\nwith exports from other countries, 1\nwith gold and American securities,;\nand finally with increasing credit\nfrom America. This government\nfinanced the purchases of Europe by\nadvancing Joafis of nearly $10,000,000,000.\nWhen loans stop>pe.d the foreign\ntrade had to be financed some other\nway; oy the extension of credit by\nexporters and then the borrowing of\nthe needed cash of the banks, to meet\nthe shortage of capital.\n\"Thus we see that the extending of\n$4,000,000,000 of floating credit to facilitate\nour export trade has been one\nof the leading factors in bringing\nabout the credit stringency in the\nUnited States, and that stringency, in\nturn, has been one large factor in\ncontributing to the recent violent decline\nin commodity prices.\"\nMr. McHugh then referred to conditions\nof our present export trade\nwith the great surpluses of field and\nfactory, and \"yet the Irony of it is\nthat the outside world could use all\nthe surplus products we might spare\nand Europe is still calling urgently\nfor goods.\"\nIt was in 1918. before the signing\nof the armistice, that the A. B. A.,\nrealising the conditions 'that were\npractically certain to come, pledged\nitself to use every means to do everything\nin its power to meet the demands\nof the export trade.\nThe Edge measure, an amendment\nto the federal reserve act, gave the\nmedium through which the formation\nof a bank, with sufficient capital to\nmake It a valuable instrument of international\nwelfare, is permitted. A\nplan waa approved by the A. B. A. for\nthe formation of a one-hundred-million-dollar\nbank; 65 per cent of the\nI A. B. A. membership expressing a\nwillingness to consider making sub'\nscriptlons to stock. The Edge act pro!\nvides that corporations may extend\nloans to the amount of ten times their\ncapital and surplus.\nNational banks are authorised to\n{nVOQt nop pant O t nanital and alto.\nplus, and in many cases state banks\nhave been authorised to make investment\nof like character in the proposed\nbank.\nMr. McHugh paid high compliment\nto the Edge act as doing abroad what\nthe federal reserve bank system has\ndone at home.\nHe stated plainly that It was not\nthe plan of the A. B. A. to organise\nsuch a bank on its own behalf. That\nif such a bank is brought into being\nit should be at the instance of the\n\"representatives of the entire country\nthrough united effort to that end.\"\nThe plan does not suggest inflation.\nWhat it does contemplate is the setting\naside through the exercise of\nsane economy of a fair percentage of\nour annual production of |70,Md,M0.\nIt suggests the investment of that\nreasonable percentage thereof in foreign\nsecurities.\nDividend Deris red.\nDirectors of the Capital Traction\nCcmpany have declared the usual\nquarterly dividend of 1H per cent,\npayable January 1, 1921, to share\nholders of record December 1Z.\nCkiyttr Aetlvlfle*.\nW. R Thurston, president of the\nBaltimore Chapter, A. I. R, will talk\nto the elementary class of Washington\nChapter Tuesday evening, December\n14. on \"The Duties of a Note\nTeller.\" Mr. Thurston is fully ac\\\nquainted with hla subject, one of\nthe very vital elements of banking,\nas it is the only money maker in the\nbusiness, other than commercial paper,\nacceptances and investments.\nWashington Stock Exchange.\n8 ALBS.\nr Washington Bwy. p#d ?5 it SS%. 20 at\nGse?28 St 4?%. I 1\nAFTKR CALU\nClir and gelmrtiea Rwy. Si?88,600 st <8,\n\\ii.ww st H??, 13.000 ?t\nRid end A eked brirM\nBONDS\nr PUBLIC UTLLJTT.\n14. Aaked.\ni An*rinu Tel. end Telfa. 4e.... 75 75%\nAmerican Tel. and Telia. 4%a.. 80% 81%\nAi*. Tel. and Tel. ctl. t*. 5?.... 77 77%\nAm. Tel. and Tel. Coot. a 04% 04%\nAnarostla and Potomac 8a 40\nAnaoatia and Potomac Goaf. 5a. 00\nbeea. and Potomac Tel. 5a.... 07 84\nCapital Traction B. K. Sa 88% 87\niTty and Suburban 8a SB\nMetropolitan R. B. 54. 01%\nI'etotnac Uetric Light 8a 88%\nPulamae Electric Cuoa. Sa 83%\nPotomac Electric Pun a l 8a 87 80\nPotomac Elee. Power G M. 8a.. 83% 04\nWart. Alex, a ad lit. V. 84.... 88\nWaaiitnaton Gaa 5a 75 78\nWash. Kwy. and Blee. 4a 50 58%\nWart. Kwy. a ad Bier. G. M. 0a 04\nMISCELLANEOUS.\nJ>. C. Papar Mff. 8a. 88\nllifga Realty 5? lloflj) SO\nBigg* Realty Sa (abort) S3\nSTOCKS\nPUBLIC UTILITY.\nAmerican Tel and 1>l*a 88\nCapital Traction *84% At\nWaatiingtoo ?.aa 40 40%\nfcerfoik and Waak. Hteambeat... ISO 300\nWaati. Rwy. and Bier com 31 21%\ntiyeb Rtry. and Klec. pfd 58% 80%\nWaahlngton-Yirginla Rwy. com. 1\nU x sh n Pti >n. V I riri n to R tlflL 4 1\nNATIONAL SANK.\nAiwncml 170 176\ni otombia 176\nComnercUl ISO in\nDtMrtet 170\nK?rni?n? aad ll