more\ndisturbing because of the prominen-e\nin the news of the day of the plight\nof the farming community and their\nunwillingness to sell their product at\nwhat they claimed would be an enormous\nloss.\nFor once cotton did not go with\nwheat; this market was steadier most\nof the time, and the focsign exchange\nmarkets, which also in the recent paet\nhave been more or less responalve to\nh? rrnin. were decidedly bet\nter, especially sterling.\nAgain the stook market had to face\nanother series of unpleas&nt items in\nthe trade news of the day. Chief oi\nthese was the monthly statement 01\nunfilled United States Steel ofders.\nwhich showed a much larger decrease\nthan had be-en looked for. Orders un\nthe books of the Steel Corporation\nwere over 800.000 tons less at the beginning\nof December ae compared\nwith the 1st of November.\nThis gave a mofe vivid picture of\nthe rapidity of the decline in the steel\ntrnde than any other presented heretofore.\nAlong with this were further reports\non wage reductions of a very\nsweeping character and accounts of\nthe tobacco growers and the wool\ntrade taking the same attitude us (lie\ngrain and cotton raisers, namely, tha<\nto sell at present prices would Involve\nintolerable losses.\nWith all that was to be said about\nthe net earnings being disappointing\nand about business depression causing\na slump in tonnage, these things could\nnot explain adequately the fact that\nmany of the low-priced rails were\ndown to prices lower than those of\nlast July, before the announcement of\nthe rate increase.\nfr\"1- Iftirtnallv ohm ?a Th view\nof the assurance given by the new\ntransportation act of a good living\nincome for the railroads of the country.\nThat it was a case of necessitous\nor distress selling rather than liquidation\nbased upon disappointment over\nthe current showing of earnings was\nmade very dear in that the decline\nwas quite as severe in the stocks of\naompantes which made a very handsome\ncomparison with last year in\ntheir September and October returns.\nThe most notable instance In point\nwas Chesapeake and Ohio. This road\nreported a very large net gain, a\ngain that was the more remarkable\nbecause it occurred in a comparison\nwith what was a very line showing\nin 191*. Yet Chesapeake and Ohio\nHUfn. urvKC guiie UB umiiv M ?LII/ UI\nthe other rails today. The higherpriced\nrail*, especially New York\nCentral and Atchison, were feeling\nthe effect of the disadvantageous\ncomparison which they make with\nSouthern Pacific. The last named, allowing\nfor the rights, was selling almost\ndown to 74. The ability of the\nSouthern Pacific to earn out of transudation\noperations at least twice the\nper cent dividend is unquestioned\nand meanwhile as the result of the\n>11 land deal a new cash equity equal\nto $11 a share on Southern Pacific\nitock has been set up.\nAt Forced Bale.\nIt was very hard to explain the\nweakness in the railway stocks in\nsny other way than that they were\nbeing sold by people who had to sell\nregardless of any consideration of\nvalue. It ought to be well understood\nby this time that the net earnings of\nSeptember and October were no fair\nsrlterion as to what the roads can do\naok In private hands and with the\n10 to 34 per cent rate increase.\nThe comparisons with last year\nwere disappointing mainly because\nsxtraordlnary appropriations will not\nbe continued during the winter\nmonths*. It Is true that the traffic of\nthe railroads will suffer by the business\ndepression.\nBut as against this there is a fact\nthat railway stocks have In many Instances\nlost all and more of their entire\ngain of the autumn and are hack\nto where they were selling previous\nto the great change in their whole\noutlook, which came with the pronouncement\nof the Interstate Commerce\nCommission.\nThe truth seems to be that various\npools in tbs low-priced rails which\nwere active In the market of two\nmonths ago have reaehed the end of\ntheir rope and been forced to unload.\nSecondly, a lot of rich lnves4mm\nIn Awdaw Ia annana tVia In.\nivio n UV, I II VI ?V VWV?|?V Hit 111\noome tax, put their money Into the\nnon-dlvidend-paylng rails stocks,\nhave been compelled by the exigencies\nof the general situation to let go.\nAs for the higher priced dividend\npayers it is a necessitous selling unquestionably\nin their oase also, for\nnobody doubts their ability under the\nnew rates and with the quasi-guarantee\nof a sufficient Income given by\nthe transportation act, to maintain\ntheir present distribution regardless\nof the depression In Industry.\nALL HIMDEINDS\nSHOW GOOD STRENGTH\nNEW TORK, December 10.?Today's\nbond market followed much the same\ncourse as that of yesterday. Standard\nInvestment Issues held up relatively well\nand In the case of liberty bonds there\nwere even some advances. Indicating that\nthe selling pressure, which was so active\nin other parts of the market, was not\nextending to the governments.\nThe market for recently floated bonds\n?that is. for issues put out during the\nlest six months or so?continued to act\nvery well.\nUnited States Rubber 7%s. for example.\nat 97%. were tip on the day and\nwere selling level with where they were\na week ago.\nBell Telephone of Pennsylvania 7s\nst 1*1% and Westinghouss Electric 7a\nat 94% were likewise down very little,\ntaking the period of the past fortnight.\nThe course of these securities\nsupplementing the quick absorption\n?f all the high-grade new offerings\ncoming out indicates that the extremely\ndisturbed conditions in business\nand in speculative Wall street\nhave not diminished the demand for\ninvestment bonds of high rank on\nwhlah the return is made sufficiently\nattractive.\nWhat weakness there was in the bond\nlist centered upon bonds of the semispeculative\ntype. The Seaboard 9s, in\nthe outside market, were off another\npoint to 4B%. St. Louie and San Francisco\nincome Is were likewise down a\npoint to 48%. Convertible bonds moving\nin sympathy with their respective\nMocks were generally lower.\nRail bonds of the higher class, like\nthe Atchison 4s at 74, which were off\nfrom their November high 3 points, were\nin demand at this level without any\nfurther inclination to sag. Traction\noonaa continued weak with the interborough\nRap id Transit 5a. at 45f?, and\nthe Third Avenue Adjustments at 24.\nSUGAR MARKET WEAK.\nNEW YORK, December 10 ?Raw\nsugar opened weak and prices declined\nto new low reccft-ds for th<\nyear. Early sales of Cuban wert\nmade at 5.27 for centrifugal and latel\nPorto JUoan was quoted at 5.41, witl\nths tone easy. Refined was unchanged\nat t.75a*.S0 for fine granulated. Suga\nfutures were weak early In sympath]\nwith the decline in raws. At nooi\nprices were 25 to 35 points lower un\nder selling by trade Intercuts an<\ncommlselon houses.\nBAR SILVER QUOTATIONS.\nNSW YORK, December 10?Ba\nsilver, domestic, ??H; foreign, 1014\nMexican dollars, S114.\nLONDON, December 10?Bar silvei\n*114 pence per on pee. Money, 414 P*\ncent. Discount rates?short and -3\nmonth blllu, g n-i?a8\\ per cent.\n\nTODAY'S B(\nNona price* (bp Briisaod A Co.) reported (w\nThe Star oeer direct New Yortt-Waahln?ton\nwire bp Frailer Co.\nCity of Part* ?a 1P21 83%\nDominion of Canada (la of llKO. ??5<*\nFrench Government So 100%\nGovernment of Hwltaertand So II*\nKingdom of Belgium 7%? 9fV?\nl\". K. of G. B. and Ireland SV4* 1021...\nV. K. of G. B. and lieland r>%* 1022.... M\nU. K. of O. B. and Ireland 5%s 1?2?.... tM**,\nu. K. of Q. B. and Ireland 5%s 1937 88%\nAmerican Tel. and Tel. cobt. 6? 94%\nArmour Co. 4^s\nAtchison, Topeka and Santa Fe fen. 4a.. 74%\nAtlantic Coast Line 10**\nBaltimore and Ohio couv. 4%s. 5*\nBaltimore and Ohio 6a.. 5??\nBaltimore and Ohio S. W. Wt. SJ?\nBethlehem Steel refd. as 77^*\nCentral of Georgia By. 6a *2\nCentral Leather ft* *?_.\nChesapeake and Ohio ctmv. 4%* 71 As\nChesapeake and Ohio fen. 4-%s 73\nChesapeake and Ohio conv. 5*.. J*j\nChi., Burlington and Quincy jt. 4a 90J4\nI Chi., Mil. and 